Offenses and shifts are independent?

## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  table4
## X-squared = 13207, df = 16, p-value < 2.2e-16

p-value is small, so we reject the null hypothesis. Offenses and shifts are not independent.

Method and offence

To find out if the type of offense has an effect on the method used we can constructing a contingency table between OFFENCE and METHOD

##         
##          ARSON ASSAULT W/DANGEROUS WEAPON BURGLARY HOMICIDE
##   GUN        0                       3409      182      447
##   KNIFE      0                       4202       53       74
##   OTHERS    89                       3490    12247       80
##         
##          MOTOR VEHICLE THEFT ROBBERY SEX ABUSE THEFT F/AUTO THEFT/OTHER
##   GUN                      4    5616        89            5          17
##   KNIFE                    1     987        87            4          30
##   OTHERS               13426    8838      1372        53639       68505

Now to check any dependency between METHOD and OFFENSE we do the Chi-square to test. In this case, the null hypoyhesis will be that the variables are independent, and the alternative hypothesis is simply that they are not. So, a small p-value means that we have to reject the null hypothesis and state that the variables are dependent. Otherwise, if the p-value is large, we fail to reject the null hypothesis and should state that the variables are indeed independents.

## Warning in chisq.test(contable): Chi-squared approximation may be incorrect
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  contable
## X-squared = 109040, df = 16, p-value < 2.2e-16

According to the result, METHOD and OFFENSE are dependent (p-value = 0). So we reject the null hypothesis Ho and state variables are dependent. So OFFENSE do have effect on METHOD

crime5yrs_nona_neightborhood <- crime5yrs[!(crime5yrs$NEIGHBORHOOD_CLUSTER == ""), ]
crime_by_neighborhood_cluster<-group_by(crime5yrs_nona_neightborhood,NEIGHBORHOOD_CLUSTER)
neighborhood_crime_count<-summarize(crime_by_neighborhood_cluster, crime_count=length(NEIGHBORHOOD_CLUSTER))
